Now, I want to point
something out

00:10:35.134 --> 00:10:36.802
because Steve is
sitting right here.

00:10:36.802 --> 00:10:38.870
He said that he was
concerned about me

00:10:38.870 --> 00:10:40.105
but look at his heart-rate.

00:10:40.105 --> 00:10:42.408
( audience laughter )

00:10:42.408 --> 00:10:45.077
He's cool as a cucumber
over there

00:10:45.077 --> 00:10:46.645
in the front boat.

00:10:46.645 --> 00:10:50.016
And I hope this leaves us with
an example and a reminder

00:10:50.016 --> 00:10:52.685
of the things that we can
do through this project

00:10:52.685 --> 00:10:54.420
and through changing our
understanding of data

00:10:54.420 --> 00:10:56.922
to bring us from a place,
where this information

00:10:56.922 --> 00:10:59.358
is something made by machines,
this information that

00:10:59.358 --> 00:11:01.827
is something that is
cold and numerical,

00:11:01.827 --> 00:11:04.797
to being something that can be
shared, can be talked about,

00:11:04.797 --> 00:11:07.166
can be performed, can
be used to tell stories,

00:11:07.166 --> 00:11:10.302
can be used to teach,
can be used to inspire.

00:11:10.302 --> 00:11:13.705
As Steve said our mission in
the Okavango is critical.

00:11:13.705 --> 00:11:16.541
We have two years to
cha-- to make change,

